<br>
yales asked for some numbers.  I have done this sort of thing before, so rather than redoing it, I went and found a thread I started on another board, called the arstechnica SoapBox.  (I heartily recommend it, but beware, it is a rough and tumble place.)  The thread in question can be found <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://arstechnica.infopop.net/OpenTopic/page?a=tpc&amp;s=50009562&amp;f=28609695&amp;m=1960953733"> here. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
As a little background, I think most current nuclear reactors are completely dangerous, stupid, and obsolete, and the only reason they have lasted so long is because coal, oil, and gas are even worse.  Thorium burning Energy Amplifiers are a vastly better way of getting nuclear electricity.  For details and links, read the cited thread, it contains many links with useful and interesting data.<br>
<br>
Now, in that thread, I calculated how much Solar would be needed to serve as our primary energy source, displacing coal, oil, gas, etc and allowing for the &quot;third world&quot; to reach our current standard of living.  For simplicity sake, I will quote the post below.  Note there was quite a bit of rebuttal on this point in the thread, but as I recall, nobody ever disputed my figures.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Somebody earlier said not to discount Solar. So I decided to crunch a few numbers.  If I screwed this up anywhere, or made a wrong assumption, please say so.<br>
Now, let's assume 1 kilowatt of power falls per square meter of surface of the Earth. Let's give solar cells an average efficiency of 10 percent. Reduce that by half again to account for transmission losses, system issues, etc. So, realistically, we can gather 1 kilowatt of power per 20 square meters of collector.<br>
<br>
Now, earlier I made an example in which I decided (somewhat arbitrarily) that the world would need 18,000 Gigawatts of power in the future. If we can gather 1 kilowatt per 20 square meters, then it will take 360,000 square kilometers of collection surface to hit that 18,000 Gigawatts. <br>
<br>
Naturally, we can't simply plate over a patch of ground solidly with collectors, so lets assume that one third of the ground is left open. That means our collectors will cover a total of 540,000 square kilometers. If we build it all in one spot, it will be about the size of France.<br>
<br>
But we can't stop yet! This array supplies power only half the time, at best! Therefore, unless we figure out a way to store gigantic amounts of power for the dark hours, we will need at least TWO of these at a minimum, and for safeties sake, three arays per hemisphere would be better. Three in the Northen Hemisphere, and three more in the Southern Hemisphere. Why? Three arrays evenly spaced in the Northern Hemisphere should have sunlight at all times, and the three in the Southern Hemisphere will assure that there should almost always be a source of power available, since the Northern and Southern Hemispheres rarely have congruent weather patterns, so one of the two sun-facing arrays should have light at all times.<br>
<br>
Where to put them? In deserts would be the sensible choice! In the Northern Hemisphere, the US desert states, the Northern Sahara, and Mongolia seem like good spots. In the Souther Hemisphere, the Australian outback, the high steppes of Argentina, and the Kalahari desert seem good choices. <br>
<br>
So, 3,240,000 square kilometers of the Earth's surface needs to be built over with huge arrays of photocells in order to reasonably assure that solar will supply all our needs.<br>
<br>
Do my figures seem off? I must confess I am a trifle astonished by the amount of area needed for this system, but this seems like the only way to really go with Solar as the primary power source. I don't see how something this huge would be realistically seen as a better alternative to advanced power plants of some kind.<br>
<br>
Also, as a note, earlier I posted that EA's making 1.5 Gigawatts aranged in 4 unit plants could supply that same 18,000 Gig with 3000 plants. Well, I screwed up my calculations. (ooops) That 1.5 gig is the THERMAL output. Converting it to electricity and transmitting it around will soak up about 80 percent of that output, so instead of 3,000 plants it would take 15,000. Still way fewer than the 100,000 or so currently in service. My bad!  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
