<br>
Hmmm.  They DO require area though....   Let's look a bit.<br>
<br>
Ok, I went to the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.census.gov/population/www/socdemo/hh-fam.html"> Census Bureau</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> site and found there are roughly 105 million households in the USA.  <br>
<br>
Let's make a simplifying assumption 100 million of them are houses.  Now for some math.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
assume 100 million houses in america.<br>
<br>
assume the average &quot;roof&quot; is 20 feet by 20 feet.<br>
6 meters by 6 meters = 36 square meters<br>
<br>
assume 25 percent of roofs are usable for PV (not shaded and south facing)  No, I will NOT assume we are going to build tracking systems for this much collector, get real. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
25 million times 36 square meters = 900,000,000 square meters.<br>
<br>
one square kilometer is one million square meters<br>
<br>
25 million roofs equals 900 square kilometers of collector<br>
<br>
So, set solar flux to 1 kilowatt per square meter, assume ten percent efficiency<br>
<br>
each roof now produces 3.6 times 1 kilowatt, or 3.6 kilowatts<br>
<br>
25 million roofs at 3.6 kilowatts is 90,000,000 kilowatts<br>
<br>
90,000 megawatts<br>
<br>
90 gigawatts<br>
<br>
Now 90 gigawatts is a LOT of generating capacity! <br>
<br>
What happens when the sun goes down?  Use windmills all night?  What if the wind doesn't blow?  Store power overnight?  How?  Lead-acid batteries?  How often do they need replacing?  Store it as hydrogen?  Is a residential electrolysis and storage system in mass production yet?  For that matter, how often do you have to replace those 25 million solar arrays?  <br>
<br>
How about clouds? Heck, what happens to a town after a hailstorm?  Armor the collectors?  What about vandalism?<br>
<br>
Dust on the collectors?  Trees growing in the way?  Graffiti?<br>
<br>
Etc, etc. <br>
<br>
Distributed models seem SO sexy.  If they work so well, why aren't they in use already?  We used to use ALL distributed models, with low-head hydro (watermills) and locally generated steam plants.  Why did those models fail?  (Economies of scale ring a bell?)<br>
<br>
Did I mention how expensive all those panels are going to be?  Who pays?  If the customers all go solar, who pays for the transmission system?  Or do you just dismantle that?<br>
